      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to all governing equations including hemolysis transport; convergence order verified to within 5% of theoretical order.",
      "rationale": "MMS verification performed for Navier-Stokes equations; hemolysis transport UDF was verified using a simplified channel flow benchmark but not via full MMS. Convergence order for hemolysis equation confirmed at 1.7 vs theoretical 2.0 (15% deviation). Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "GCI below 2% for NIH at all five VAD operating points using Richardson extrapolation on three mesh levels; y+ < 1 on all blood-contacting surfaces.",
      "rationale": "GCI study demonstrated 1.8% for NIH at the medium-to-fine mesh transition. However, y+ values on the impeller tip clearance surfaces reached 1.4 at the highest RPM operating point, marginally exceeding the y+ < 1 criterion. Achieved level 4 against required level 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental validation conditions must match VAD COU operating points within ±5% for flow rate and ±2% for rotational speed; blood analogue fluid rheology characterised at physiological temperature.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experiments used glycerol-water blood analogue at 37°C. Flow rate matching within 3%; rotational speed matching within 1.5%. However, hematocrit of analogue fluid was 0% (Newtonian) versus physiological 40–45%, introducing rheological non-equivalence for hemolysis prediction. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation metric (E_val) for NIH must satisfy U_num + U_exp > |E_val| with combined uncertainty below 15% of the clinical threshold; comparison must cover all five VAD operating points.",
      "rationale": "Experimental comparison achieved mean absolute error 0.008 g/100 L across 12 FDA pump operating points. However, only 3 of 5 VAD-specific operating points fall within the validated flow-speed envelope. The two highest-RPM points (3000 and 3200 RPM) are extrapolations beyond the experimental dataset. Achieved level 3 against required level 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation (NIH, wall shear stress distribution, pressure-flow characteristic) must directly map to the regulatory decision quantities without surrogate substitution.",
      "rationale": "NIH is the primary regulatory QoI and is directly predicted and validated. Pressure-flow characteristic validated against pump curve data with R²=0.997. Wall shear stress distribution validated qualitatively via PIV data. Full correspondence between validation QoIs and COU decision quantities confirmed. Achieved level 4."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must use the same pump geometry as the VAD COU device; blood or equivalent analogue must be used; operating conditions must span the full VAD envelope.",
      "rationale": "Validation used the FDA generic centrifugal pump, which is a different geometry from the specific VAD device under assessment. Geometric similarity is moderate (same impeller class, different blade count and tip clearance). This represents a significant relevance gap at MRL 5. Achieved level 3 against required level 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence to residuals below 1e-6 for all equations; mass imbalance below 0.01%; demonstration that solver settings (relaxation factors, discretisation schemes) do not introduce bias in hemolysis prediction.",
      "rationale": "Residuals converged to 1e-5 for continuity and momentum; hemolysis transport equation residual stalled at 8e-5 for the two highest-RPM operating points due to recirculation zones in the volute. Mass imbalance 0.03%, above the 0.01% criterion. Solver error contribution to NIH uncertainty estimated at 12%. Achieved level 2 against required level 4.",
      "prov:wasDerivedFrom": "https://uofa.net/synth/evidence/solver-convergence-logs-cou2"
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented simulation protocol with independent peer review; analyst qualification records; at least one blind re-analysis by a second analyst confirming NIH predictions within 5%.",
      "rationale": "Simulation protocol documented and internally reviewed. Analyst holds PhD in computational fluid dynamics with 8 years of cardiovascular CFD experience. Independent blind re-analysis was not performed; a second analyst reviewed the setup but used the same mesh and boundary conditions prepared by the primary analyst. Achieved level 2 against required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Hemolysis model form (power-law vs mechanistic) must be justified against published literature for the specific shear stress and exposure time regime of the VAD; turbulence model selected with demonstrated applicability to rotating blood-contacting geometries.",
      "rationale": "Power-law Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis model used. This model was calibrated on Couette flow data and is known to overpredict hemolysis in complex rotating geometries by factors of 2–10 (Taskin et al., 2012). SST k-omega turbulence model selected; applicability to the tip clearance gap flow is uncertain. Model form uncertainty is the dominant epistemic gap. Achieved level 2 against required level 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All hemolysis model coefficients characterised with uncertainty bounds from peer-reviewed sources; inlet velocity profile measured or validated; fluid properties at physiological conditions documented.",
      "rationale": "Hemolysis power-law coefficients (C, alpha, beta) sourced from Giersiepen et al. (1990) with uncertainty bounds from Fraser et al. (2012) meta-analysis. Inlet velocity profile assumed fully developed; no PIV measurement of actual inlet profile. Blood viscosity modelled as Newtonian (3.5 mPa·s); non-Newtonian effects not characterised. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental hemolysis measurements must use fresh human blood or validated porcine blood analogue with documented hematocrit, age, and storage conditions; minimum n=5 independent samples per operating point.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark dataset uses glycerol-water analogue (not blood); sample size and biological variability data not available from the published dataset. This factor cannot be assessed from available evidence. Flagged as epistemic gap at MRL 5. Achieved level 1 against required level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Formal equivalency mapping between validation experiment input parameters and VAD COU input parameters must be documented; any non-equivalent parameters must be addressed via sensitivity analysis or additional validation.",
      "rationale": "No formal equivalency mapping document exists for the transition from FDA generic pump validation to the specific VAD COU. Geometric, rheological, and operating condition differences are acknowledged in the simulation report but not formally quantified. This factor is not assessed. Achieved level 1 against required level 4."
